          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":55,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Easy long run at 5:22–5:56/km. Cap at 20 km or 120 min. Focus on relaxed effort and good form. This anchors your week and maintains your aerobic base.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Recovery is where adaptation happens — treat this as active investment in the week ahead.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy at 5:22–5:56/km. Shake out the legs from Sunday. Conversational effort only — if in doubt, slow down.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"notes\":\"12 km total: 2 km warm-up, 8 km at threshold pace (4:28/km), 2 km cool-down. This is your key quality session of the week — steady, controlled effort at the edge of comfortably hard.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"6 km easy recovery run at 5:45–5:56/km. Keep this genuinely easy — it flushes fatigue from yesterday's tempo without adding stress.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"notes\":\"10 km total: 2 km warm-up, 5×1 km at interval pace (4:11/km) with 400 m jog recovery, ~1.6 km cool-down. Second quality session — these sharpen your aerobic ceiling and keep your legs feeling quick.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"8 km easy at 5:22–5:56/km. A comfortable end to the week. Notice how your legs feel — that's useful data heading into next week.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome, Maria! This first maintenance week mirrors what your training history shows you're already handling well — around 55 km with two quality sessions and a 20 km long run. The structure is intentionally familiar: one tempo, one interval session, and the rest easy. Your VDOT of 46.7 reflects genuine fitness built over years of consistent work, and the goal right now is to hold that without grinding. The paces are drawn directly from your race history using Daniels' formula, so trust them — especially on easy days where slowing down is the point, not a compromise. One thing worth keeping an eye on: your Achilles history. Nothing in this week's plan should provoke it, but if you notice any morning stiffness or tightness on the left side, that's worth flagging before it becomes anything more. How does this structure feel to you — does the day layout work with your week?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
